me person's name occurring with and without <i>-(e)s</i> have been noted as early as the 14th century in South Lancashire. The <i>-es</i> in such cases probably has neither a plural nor a genitival function, and the name means ‘dweller at the brook’, not ‘dweller at the brooks’. A plural sense cannot be ruled out elsewhere, but a non-grammatical <i>-(e)s</i> must also be considered a strong possibility.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","Americanized form of German   Brucks  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Brucks","meanings":["North German:","probably a habitational name from Brucks (also Brux) which derives from Middle Low German <i>brōk</i> ‘low-lying marsh’.","reportedly also an altered form of Flemish (Dutch) <b>Broex</b>, an old variant of <b>Broeks</b> (see   Brooks  )."]},{"name":"Brook","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by a brook, stream, water-meadows or low, marshy ground, from Middle English <i>brook</i>, Old English <i>brōc</i> ‘brook, stream’; or a habitational name from any of various places called with this word, such as Brook (Kent, Rutland) or Brooke (Norfolk).","North German: topographic name for someone who lived by a water meadow or marsh, from Low German <i>brook</i> (cognate with German   Bruch   ‘swamp’ and Old English <i>brōc</i>; see 1 above).","Americanized form of Dutch <b>Broek</b>: topographic name from <i>broek</i>, a cognate of 2 above."]},{"name":"Brookes","meanings":["English (West Midlands): variant of   Brooks  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John BROOKS was born about 1185, in Oakley, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Brooks, was 22 and his mother, Mrs- William Brooks, was 19. He married Mrs John Brooks about 1214, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"ABT 1185–":"umbes 1185–Surnud","1185–Male"